http://www.wizards.com/Magic/Magazine/A ... y/boab/186Ouch! Dude put Ponder in a modern deck (where Ponder is banned) and then made it sound like he practiced on MTGO with it against other decks, which he couldn't (as Ponder is banned). So either he's just playing against his brother in unrestricted casual (could be and that's fine if he told the truth) or he just outright made up the results of the matches and he's been doing that for years.I don't want to crucify the dude, and again, I think testing at his convenience against friends (of average or slightly above skill) is just fine. But the one single selling point he had over Ben Bleiweiss (who previously wrote the column) was that he tested against tourney room decks and not just casual roomers.Ben also mentioned opponents by name/MTGO handle, which I sometimes thought was inappropriate (although I enjoyed him calling out people by name who played dragonstorm in the casual room and other completely degenerate decks and enjoyed seeing names of people I'd played against before; it made me feel like I was part of the whole magic experience), given that he was beating up on non-pros, often with decks even more budget than his building on the budget builds.I thought that maybe van Lunen stopped that for that reason, but maybe he stopped listing names because he invented the games or always played against the same two or three buds.OTOH, if it's just real life testing he's doing, it'd be nice to feature his local store / kitchen table and people to humanize the column a bit with some photos, especially since he's not letting us feel like we're participating in a community by reading the column (even though I don't think I ever played against Ben myself, personally).I'm not sympathetic to the view that he doesn't have time to write + playtest a deck every week so shortcuts are acceptable.OTOH, I am sympathetic to the point of view that wotc doesn't print enough wicked cards to do the sort of thing Ben did back in Rav/TSP -- as most of his best decks weren't about turning creatures sideways.I mean how many different asshole things could you do with cloudstone curio in every freaking color? There's not much similar to that in modern sets. Losing stacked damage wrecked a lot of the possibilities for incremental advantage decks, too, which were a budget specialty. Plus the whole mythic and planeswalker thing.
