Quote:It was a massively frustrating experience all in all.Welcome to standard. That's what happens when you have terrible card pools, you get terrible sealed and draft pools and games become terrible deck vs terrible deck and if anyone sticks a bomb, forget it game over. Quote:I mean how many different asshole things could you do with cloudstone curio in every freaking color? There's not much similar to that in modern sets. Losing stacked damage wrecked a lot of the possibilities for incremental advantage decks, too, which were a budget specialty. Plus the whole mythic and planeswalker thing. I don't think the stacking damage thing was that big a deal. All it did was make sac effects stronger than they should have been. IMHO, the loss of incrimental advantage came from planeswalkers and WAY overpowering the 6 drop spot. Jon Finkle was talking about it in some article or something, he nailed it by saying that so many games tody are decided by who sticks the first 6 drop. It makes the game way more swingy, which is good for variance if thats what you want, but terrible for deckbuilders and players who want to build decks that win by being a little better than the opposing deck. You can't get an incrimental advatage over a titan. You need to kill it and drop your own. Which is why decks looks like they do today.
